            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Isla Montoya-Pascual is a daughter of the Mission District in every sense of the word. Born to a Filipino immigrant father who worked as a union cook and a second-generation Mexican-American mother who was a teacher\u2019s aide, Isla\u2019s childhood was a vibrant tapestry of culture, activism, and community. She grew up in the loud, colorful, politically charged atmosphere of 1970s and \u201880s San Francisco, her identity shaped by the murals on Balmy Alley and the dual languages spoken at her dinner table.\n\nWitnessing the devastation of the AIDS epidemic tear through her community was the crucible that forged her path. She saw friends and neighbors suffer not just from the disease, but from systemic neglect. This galvanized her. She enrolled at San Francisco State University, earning both her bachelor's and master's degrees in Social Work, determined to build the support systems her community desperately needed.\n\nHer career began on the front lines as a caseworker in the very neighborhoods she grew up in. Over two decades, her fierce advocacy and profound empathy saw her rise through the ranks. A key turning point was a difficult but necessary divorce in her early forties from a partner whose idealism had soured into cynicism. The split refocused Isla, leading her tochannel her energy wholly into her work, eventually earning her the role of Program Director.\n\nToday, Isla\u2019s life is one of disciplined purpose. She lives in a rent-controlled apartment in Bernal Heights, just a 1.8-mile bike ride from her clinic. Her days start with tending to her balcony garden and end with a book club, a community board meeting, or a quiet dinner with her \u2018chosen family\u2019 of close friends. She is a beloved fixture in her neighborhood, fiercely protective of its character against the relentless waves of gentrification.\n\nHer deepest aspiration is to secure permanent funding for a new youth mental health initiative at her clinic, creating a legacy of care for the next generation. Personally, she dreams of one day taking an extended trip to both the Philippines and Mexico, to finally walk the lands of the ancestors whose stories have fueled her lifelong fight for others."
